          "body": "Jacob's angry response to Rachel in verse 2 is the chapter's theological thesis: 'Am I in the place of God, who has withheld from you the fruit of the womb?' This is not merely irritation at an unfair demand. It is a confession of divine sovereignty over fertility that the entire chapter then dramatizes. Rachel attempts to circumvent God's withholding through surrogacy (30:3), through mandrakes (30:14–15), and through bargaining (30:16) — and all of these efforts are rendered ironic when God simply 'remembered Rachel' (30:22) and she conceived. The sovereign act that Rachel could not produce through any of her strategies comes as pure divine gift. Calvin noted on this passage that 'it is not in our power to give or to take away children; since that authority belongs to God alone' — and the chapter demonstrates it at length."
