          "body": "The mandrake episode (30:14–21) is the chapter's sharpest piece of narrative irony. Mandrakes (*duday*) — the *Mandragora officinarum* — were widely believed in the ancient Near East to be a fertility aid; their root resembles a human body and their berries were thought to stimulate conception. Rachel wants them desperately enough to barter away Jacob's company for an entire night. She gets the mandrakes. She does not conceive. Leah surrenders the mandrakes and conceives Issachar, then Zebulun, then Dinah (30:17–21). Only after all of this — after the mandrake strategy has demonstrably failed — does the narrator report that 'God remembered Rachel' (30:22). The sequence is deliberate. The narrator is closing every human door before opening the divine one. The fertility charm is inert; God is not."
