          "body": "Verse 22 is the chapter's theological center of gravity: 'Then God remembered Rachel, and God gave heed to her and opened her womb.' The verb *zakhar* — to remember — never refers in the Old Testament to God recovering a forgotten fact. It refers to God acting in history on the basis of a prior covenant commitment. The same verb governs God's action toward Noah (8:1), toward Abraham on behalf of Lot (19:29), toward Israel in Egypt (Exod 2:24), and toward Hannah (1 Sam 1:19). In every instance, divine 'remembering' is not intellectual recollection but covenantal intervention. Rachel's barrenness was not an oversight; its end was a sovereign act. The opened womb (30:22) answers the closed womb of 29:31 — God had closed Leah's and opened Rachel's in the previous chapter; now He reverses course. Both opening and closing belong to Him."
