        "excerpt": "God gave heed to Leah, and she conceived and bore Jacob a fifth son.",
        "body": "The mandrake episode is the chapter's most complex narrative unit. Reuben — Leah's firstborn, old enough to work in the fields during wheat harvest — brings his mother a find of mandrakes (*duday*). The plant's folk-medicinal reputation for stimulating fertility makes it an obvious object of desire for Rachel, who immediately requests them. Leah's response is bitter: 'Is it a small matter for you to take my husband? And would you take my son's mandrakes also?' The accusation that Rachel has 'taken' Jacob echoes the marriage dynamics of Genesis 29 — Leah has been the unloved wife, experiencing Jacob's conjugal presence as rationed and negotiated. The mandrake request feels like one more appropriation from a sister who already has Jacob's heart.\n\nRachel's counter-offer is stunning in its candor: 'Therefore he may lie with you tonight in return for your son's mandrakes.' Jacob's conjugal access is being bartered between his wives like a commercial commodity. When Jacob returns from the field that evening, Leah intercepts him with the announcement: 'You must come in to me, for I have surely hired you' (*sakhar*) with my son's mandrakes.' Jacob is passive throughout this entire episode — he goes where he is directed. The wives are the agents; he is the instrument.\n\nThe narrative irony is the chapter's most pointed. Rachel secured the mandrakes — and the text never records her conceiving from them. Leah gave up the mandrakes — and God gave heed to Leah (30:17). She conceives Issachar, then Zebulun, and bears a daughter Dinah (30:19–21). The fertility charm sought by Rachel produces nothing; the woman who surrendered the charm receives divine attention. The contrast could not be more deliberate: human fertility strategies (mandrakes, surrogacy, negotiated access) are all rendered inert. What produces children is God's sovereign 'giving heed' (*shama* — listen, attend to).\n\nLeah's naming theology deepens here. Issachar — 'God has given me my wages' (30:18) — reflects her sense that she is receiving from God what is owed her for giving Zilpah to Jacob. Zebulun — rooted in *zaval* (to honor, dwell with) — expresses her hope that Jacob will now dwell with her permanently (30:20). Both names record Leah's ongoing longing for the love of a husband whose heart belongs elsewhere. The pathos of Leah's situation is a consistent undercurrent in the birth narrative — she has borne six sons and still must hope that the next one will produce what children cannot.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Duday* (mandrakes) — *Mandragora officinarum*; the root of the name may connect to *dod* (beloved), reinforcing the fertility-love association. *Sakhar* (hired, wages) — the same word used in the wages negotiation of 30:28, 32, 33; the mandrake transaction uses commercial language for what is intimate and personal. *Shama* (gave heed) in v. 17 — literally 'heard/listened to'; God's attentiveness to Leah is narrated in the same vocabulary as His response to Rachel's crying voice in verse 6."
