        "excerpt": "For you had little before I came and it has increased to a multitude, and the LORD has blessed you wherever I turned.",
        "body": "Joseph's birth triggers Jacob's announcement that he is ready to leave (30:25–26). The fourteen years of service for Leah and Rachel are complete; Jacob has no independent household resources; it is time to return to Canaan and to Isaac. His claim is grounded not in grievance but in documented service: 'You yourself know how I have served you and how your cattle have fared with me' (30:29). The framing is contractual and dignified.\n\nLaban's counter-move is instructive. He does not appeal to kinship or loyalty; he appeals to self-interest: 'I have divined that the LORD has blessed me on your account' (30:27). The verb *nachash* (to practice divination) is striking — Laban is apparently using pagan divination to track the source of his prosperity, and even that pagan method confirms the covenantal reality. Jacob then states it plainly: 'The LORD has blessed you wherever I turned' (30:30). Both men acknowledge the theological fact. Neither man acts on it in a straightforwardly honest way: Laban will attempt to keep Jacob as a blessed employee indefinitely; Jacob will devise a scheme to extract maximum compensation before departing. The acknowledgment of YHWH's blessing does not produce virtue in either party — it produces strategic calculation.\n\nJacob's wages proposal (30:31–34) appears straightforward: he will take only the speckled, spotted, and dark-colored animals as they are born — a minority category in normal Near Eastern herds. But Laban immediately corrupts the agreement on the same day (30:35): he removes all the currently existing marked animals and hands them to his sons, ensuring that Jacob's starting flock is zero. The three-day buffer (30:36) prevents any mixing of the herds. Laban's preemptive action is a violation of the spirit of the agreement, though Jacob's proposal had not explicitly addressed existing animals.\n\nJacob's response is the famous rod-peeling scheme (30:37–42): he takes fresh branches of poplar, almond, and plane trees, peels white stripes into them, and places them in the watering troughs where the flocks mate. The result is a disproportionate production of striped and speckled offspring (30:39). Jacob then applies the scheme selectively — using the rods only when the stronger animals mate, withholding them when the weaker animals mate — so that the stronger offspring accrue to him and the weaker to Laban (30:41–42).\n\nModern interpreters have debated whether Jacob's technique reflects ancient folk-genetic beliefs about maternal impression (the idea that what an animal sees during mating influences offspring color) or whether it represents something else entirely. The decisive interpretive datum is Genesis 31:10–12, where God tells Jacob in a dream that the outcome of the breeding was divinely directed — the angel showed Jacob the striped and spotted males covering the flock as a divine disclosure, not a natural outcome of the rod technique. The rod-peeling was Jacob's scheme; the covenant prosperity was God's provision. Laban could remove every existing marked animal; he could not remove the LORD's blessing from Jacob's labor. The chapter ends with Jacob 'exceedingly prosperous' (30:43) — *meod meod*, twice-emphatic, the vocabulary of covenant abundance.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nachash* (divined, 30:27) — to practice divination, observe omens; later explicitly prohibited in Israel (Lev 19:26; Deut 18:10), but here the divination accurately perceives YHWH's blessing, an irony the narrator leaves uncommented. *Parats* (prosperous, 30:43) — to break out, to spread; the same verb as in Exodus 1:12 and Genesis 28:14 where the promise to Jacob includes spreading like the dust of the earth. *Meod meod* — 'exceedingly exceedingly' — the double intensifier marks covenant-scale increase, not merely commercial success."
